4,905 Likes
Most AI coding benchmarks ask one question: does the code work?
FrontierCode
, a new benchmark from Cognition, asks something harder: would a real maint=
ainer actually merge it?
That shift matters. AI models have gotten good at writing code that passes =
tests but is messy, out of scope, or ignores a project's style. FrontierCod=
e catches all of that.
Here is what it actually grades:
Correctness, yes, but also test quality and regression safety
Scope discipline: did the model change only what it needed to?
Style and adherence to that specific codebase's standards
The tasks were built by maintainers of
36 real open-source repos
, each spending 40+ hours per task. It has three tiers: Extended, Main, and=
 Diamond.
The results are humbling. On the hardest Diamond set, the top model scores =
just
13.4 out of 100
. It also produces
81% fewer grading errors
than SWE-Bench Pro, so the scores you see actually mean something.
For you, this is a much more honest signal of whether an AI tool is ready f=
or your real codebase.
